{
  "id": "c-moivk7pd-7bedba64b71a",
  "goal": "Lifecycle interactions between Reckoner gating, arbitrary writ types' custom lifecycles, and inter-writ relationships. Reckoner uses new→open as the accept transition — this works cleanly for mandates but assumes the writ type's active phase is named 'open'. How does this generalize to writ types with custom lifecycles (e.g. cartograph charges/pieces have draft|active|... stages and may have non-'open' first active phases)? Second concern: there is currently no way to DRAFT a writ before sending it to the petitioner other than omitting ext.reckoner — once ext is set, the writ is live for Reckoner consideration. This means parent/child or 'follows' dependency relationships cannot be set up before dispatch without risking the target writ being accepted and dispatched before its dependents are wired. Third concern: deadlock potential — if the Reckoner has a WIP limit and accepts a batch of writs that all 'follows'-depend on unaccepted petitions still queued, the accepted writs sit blocked waiting on petitions that may never get capacity to be considered. Need to think through whether a draft-state-before-petition mechanism is needed, whether dependencies should be Reckoner-aware (defer accept until dependencies are clear), and how active-phase naming generalizes per writ-type.",
  "status": "concluded",
  "createdAt": "2026-04-28T17:03:08.545Z",
  "parentId": "c-moa42rxh-d965072428ba",
  "conclusion": "Three lifecycle-interaction concerns resolved with three follow-up children opened.\n\n**Concern 1 (active-phase naming) — already solved at the implementation level.** The Reckoner's resolveActiveTargetPhase walks the writ-type's registered state machine, finds states reachable from the current phase whose classification is 'active', picks the unique candidate, and fail-louds on 0 or 2+. It does NOT hardcode 'open'. For mandate/vision/charge/piece (all six-state new→open→...) it picks 'open' automatically; for a future writ type with new→active it would pick 'active'. The unstated invariant — 'a Reckoner-gated writ type must have exactly one initial→active transition' — is enforced at runtime via fail-loud; no need to lift to writ-type-registration validation in v0. Revisit if/when a second non-mandate writ type opts into Reckoner gating.\n\n**Concern 2 (drafting before petitioning) — workable today, ergonomics gap to close.** The Reckoner gates on ext.reckoner being present (not phase alone), and re-fires on ext.reckoner change (D14). So the draft idiom is: create writ in 'new' WITHOUT ext.reckoner (invisible to Reckoner), set up parent/child + depends-on links, then patch ext.reckoner to publish. Atomic multi-writ setup composes with Stacks transactions. Cross-apparatus authoring (apparatus X creates A, apparatus Y wants B-follows-A) remains an exotic case parked for now. Ergonomics: the publish step needs a first-class API. Follow-up child c-moiwnb9i opens reckoner.petition(writId, ext) helper.\n\n**Concern 3 (WIP-cap deadlock) — Option A: Reckoner-aware dependencies.** Without intervention, the Reckoner can accept a batch of dependent writs whose dependencies are still pending petitions, fill the WIP cap with gated writs in 'open', and starve the dependencies. Resolution: Reckoner reads outbound depends-on links during consideration; if any direct target is non-terminal, defer the petition with defer_reason='dependency' (slots into c-modaqnpt's existing defer machinery). Deferred writs stay in 'new', don't count against WIP, capacity is preserved for the dependencies. Rejected Option B (topological priority bonus — only shifts probability, doesn't eliminate the deadlock), Option C (Spider flags gated writs back to Reckoner — violates c-mof657j4's no-cross-layer-coordination principle), Option D (decline-and-re-emit — pushes bookkeeping onto petitioners, hostile to recursive vision-keeper cascades). Follow-up child c-moiwnmoc opens the design detail (wake-up semantics, target-phase semantics, cycle handling).\n\n**Coupled decision: rename spider.follows → depends-on, Clerk-contributed (unprefixed).** Once the Reckoner reads the dependency link, it's no longer Spider-private. Renaming captures the framework-neutral intent ('B blocked until A reaches terminal-success'). Establishes a broader naming-primacy principle: foundational plugins that own a substrate (Clerk owns the writ graph) get the unique privilege of contributing unprefixed link kinds; everything else is plugin-namespaced (spider.*, astrolabe.*, cartograph.*). Follow-up child c-moiwnzw6 owns the rename + the primacy-principle codification.\n\nChildren opened: c-moiwnb9i (reckoner.petition helper), c-moiwnmoc (Reckoner dependency-aware consideration), c-moiwnzw6 (depends-on rename + Clerk naming primacy).",
  "resolvedAt": "2026-04-28T17:34:33.989Z",
  "resolvedSessionId": "ae7f4ae1-3b00-4a84-a8d5-35d1be7f1aba",
  "links": {
    "outbound": [],
    "inbound": []
  },
  "parent": {
    "id": "c-moa42rxh-d965072428ba",
    "goal": "Design the vision-keeper role — the agent/apparatus that holds a forward-looking product vision and decomposes it into commissionable work",
    "status": "live"
  },
  "children": {
    "summary": {
      "concluded": 1,
      "live": 4
    },
    "items": [
      {
        "id": "c-moix6ovo-404015d0e1bb",
        "goal": "Manually migrate existing WritLinkDoc rows from kind='spider.follows' to kind='depends-on' in the live guild's link store, after the rename commission (w-moix2b56-19767872adb9) ships. Out-of-band operational work — the dispatch pipeline has no guild-database access, so the migration is performed directly by Coco/Sean against the live stacks DB rather than included in the artificer's commission. Trigger: as soon as possible after the rename writ lands, to minimize the window where existing 'spider.follows' edges are orphaned (Spider's gate evaluation will be filtering on 'depends-on' and find no edges; Astrolabe's observation-lift will be writing 'depends-on' going forward; legacy rows sit unreferenced until migrated). Open: exact mechanism (direct stacks DB patch via Book.patch on the writ-links book? a small script? CLI invocation?), whether to pre-create 'depends-on' rows alongside the existing 'spider.follows' rows before the rename ships (closes the orphan window entirely, but adds a coordination step), and validation step after migration (count of 'spider.follows' rows should be zero, count of 'depends-on' rows should match the prior 'spider.follows' count). Note that link doc ids are computed from (sourceId, targetId, label) — the kind is a mutable field on the existing row, so migration is an in-place patch, not a delete-and-recreate.",
        "status": "live"
      },
      {
        "id": "c-moiwnzw6-4a2801d08a34",
        "goal": "Rename spider.follows → depends-on as a Clerk-contributed (unprefixed) link kind, and establish the principle that the Clerk plugin holds primacy of naming for framework-level link kinds. Two coupled decisions: (1) The semantic relationship 'B is blocked until A reaches a terminal-success phase' is fundamental to writ-graph structure, not Spider-internal — Reckoner needs to read it for dependency-aware consideration (sibling click), Spider continues to gate dispatch on it, and any future apparatus reasoning about writ ordering reads the same edge. Renaming to 'depends-on' captures the intent in framework-neutral terms. (2) The Clerk plugin is the framework writ-graph owner and gets the unique privilege of contributing link kinds without a plugin prefix. Plugin-namespaced link kinds (spider.*, astrolabe.*, cartograph.*) remain the default — those plugins own private edges. Unprefixed kinds (depends-on, possibly others later) are Clerk-contributed and represent universal writ-graph semantics every writ-aware operator can rely on. This establishes a 'primacy of naming' convention: foundational plugins that own a substrate get an unprefixed namespace within that substrate. Migration shape: introduce 'depends-on' as a Clerk-registered link kind, add the new kind to Spider's gate-evaluation reader (accept either kind during transition), backfill data via a one-shot CDC migration, retire the spider.follows reads. Open: exact namespace mechanism (does the Clerk register link kinds with a registry the way it registers writ types? or are link kinds free-form strings with the prefix convention purely a soft rule?), audit/enforce no-collision rule between Clerk's namespace and plugin-prefixed kinds, doc placement for the primacy principle (likely guild-vocabulary tome plus framework architecture doc).",
        "status": "live"
      },
      {
        "id": "c-moiwnmoc-bb598749904c",
        "goal": "Design Reckoner dependency-aware consideration (Option A) — Reckoner reads outbound depends-on links during consideration; if any direct target is non-terminal, defer the petition with defer_reason='dependency' instead of accepting. Resolves concern 3 of c-moivk7pd (WIP-cap deadlock): without this, the Reckoner can accept a batch of dependent writs whose dependencies are still pending petitions, fill the WIP cap with gated writs sitting in 'open', and starve the dependencies of acceptance capacity. With this, dependents stay in 'new' (don't count against WIP) until their dependencies clear, naturally preserving topological accept order. Open questions: (1) wake-up semantics — re-evaluate every tick (cheap, polling matches scheduling-trigger conclusion c-mod9a54n) or fire on writ-completion CDC events (more responsive, requires defer_signal infrastructure from c-modaqnpt)? (2) which target phases count as 'cleared' — Spider's existing logic treats {completed, cancelled} as released and {failed} as cascade-to-stuck; should the Reckoner mirror the same set, or use writ-type-config classification ('terminal' + 'success' attr)? (3) dangling references — Spider treats missing targets as still-gated; Reckoner should match. (4) cycle handling — Spider already detects cycles in the depends-on graph; Reckoner consideration should also surface cycles before accepting, or rely on Spider to fail-loud post-accept? Coordinates with the depends-on rename (sibling click) for the link-kind reading; short-term Reckoner can read 'spider.follows' until the rename lands.",
        "status": "concluded"
      },
      {
        "id": "c-moiwnb9i-391a66734c2b",
        "goal": "Add reckoner.petition(writId, ext) helper that publishes a draft writ by patching ext.reckoner onto an already-created writ. Resolves concern 2 of c-moivk7pd (drafting before petitioning): the existing draft idiom — create writ in 'new' phase WITHOUT ext.reckoner, set up parent/child links and depends-on relationships, then patch ext.reckoner to publish — works mechanically but is undiscoverable. The helper makes the publish step a first-class Reckoner API: takes a writ id and the ext payload (source, priority, complexity), patches the writ via Clerk, fires the existing CDC re-evaluation gate (D14, ext.reckoner change). Atomic multi-writ setup remains: callers wrap create + link + petition() in a Stacks transaction. Worked example: vision-keeper creates a charge writ in 'new' (no ext), creates depends-on link to its review-vision parent, calls reckoner.petition(chargeId, {...}). Open: shape of the ext argument (typed ReckonerExt vs raw object), idempotency on double-publish (no-op if ext already set vs error), patch-vs-replace semantics if ext is partially populated.",
        "status": "live"
      }
    ]
  }
}

